# Pem project

## Coding philosophy

- **Simplicity first.** If it feels too complex, simplify before adding more.
- **No over-engineering.** Solve the problem in front of you, not hypothetical future ones.
- **Clarity over cleverness.** Prefer obvious code and modern, standard patterns.
- **Short, focused files.** If a file is doing too much, split it.
- **Consistent naming and patterns** across the repo.
- **DRY:** centralize shared behavior; don’t copy-paste logic.
- **Meaningful layout:** a file’s folder should signal its role (see stack-specific `.mdc` files).
- **Docs with code:** when behavior, structure, or APIs change, update **`README.md`** and relevant **`.mdc`** in the same effort—not only after. **Stale rules mislead** — worse than missing docs.
- **Reuse before reinventing:** Before writing new helpers, check **framework and library APIs** (Expo, React Native, NestJS, Drizzle, etc.) and **existing code in this repo**—prefer extending or composing what’s already there over duplicating behavior.

**When in doubt:** Prefer a quick alignment question over a large wrong implementation. Flag assumptions in PRs or reviews. If two approaches are equal, pick the **simpler** one.

*(This complements **Collaboration** below: substantial work still follows “plan first, then code”—see that section.)*

**Product (Pem):** A mobile product for **busy minds** — users **dump** thoughts (text); Pem **preps** (search, research, options, drafts) in parallel; users **come back** to **preps** ready to act on and mark done. Pem does the **middle work** between “I need to deal with this” and “I’m ready” — **not** a chatbot to babysit or a task manager to maintain; **you** always perform the final action (send, buy, decide). Full product story, prep types table, and navigation direction: **repo `README.md`** (*What is Pem?*).

**Brand & color:** For **palette, typography, logo usage, voice** when unsure, read **`brand/pem-brand.html`** in the repo (browser) and **`brand/README.md`**. Implementations should stay aligned with **`app/constants/theme.ts`** and **`app/constants/typography.ts`**.

**Layout:** `app/` = mobile client, `backend/` = HTTP API (NestJS + Drizzle). Treat them as separate packages; do not assume shared runtime code between them.

**Stacks (authoritative):**

| Area | Stack |
|------|--------|
| Mobile | **Expo ~54**, **React 19**, **React Native**, **expo-router** (file-based routes), **TypeScript** (strict), **New Architecture** + **React Compiler** (see `app/app.json` experiments) |
| API | **`backend/`** — **Node**, **NestJS**, **Drizzle ORM**, **PostgreSQL** (`pg`), **Clerk** (JWT via **jose** + JWKS, webhooks via **Svix**), **@nestjs/throttler**, **@nestjs/swagger** (`/docs` when not prod) |

**Conventions:** Prefer small, focused changes; match existing naming (`Pem*` UI primitives in `app/`, Nest modules in `backend/`). Run `expo lint` in `app/` and `npm run lint` in `backend/` when editing those trees.

**`README.md` as source of truth:** The repo-root **`README.md`** is canonical **human-facing documentation** (stack, layout, how to run, env, contributor workflow). Whenever a change affects what contributors need to know—**new packages**, **dependencies**, **patterns**, **setup**, **commands**, or **folder roles**—**update `README.md` in the same effort** so it stays accurate. Do not leave README stale while code or `.mdc` files move ahead.

**Keeping `.cursor/rules` in sync (mandatory bar):** Any change that would confuse a new contributor or an agent if the rules stayed old **must** update the right docs in the **same PR / same coding session** — not “later.” This is how we stay on track; skipping it is a process failure.

| What changed | Update (non-exhaustive) |
|----------------|-------------------------|
| **DB** — Drizzle schema, new/renamed columns, table drops | Edit **`src/database/schemas/`** only; run **`npm run db:generate`** (never hand-write SQL under `drizzle/` or hand-edit `meta/`). See **Drizzle workflow** below. Update `pem-backend.mdc` + `backend/README.md` when workflow or tables change. |
| **API** — routes, payloads, SSE/event names, auth | `pem-backend.mdc`; keep DTOs / OpenAPI accurate; **`app/lib/pemApi.ts`** types when the client consumes it |
| **Styling & UI architecture** — tokens, navigation routes, new patterns | `pem-app.mdc`; **`app/constants/theme.ts`** & **typography** stay the implementation source of truth |
| **Product / strategy** — what Pem is, intake, naming (“prep” vs actionables, etc.) | `pem-thought-organizer.mdc`, `pem-product-brief.mdc`, **`README.md`** *What is Pem?* — whichever files own that story |
| **Dependencies, env vars, scripts, folder roles** | `pem-project.mdc` stack table; **root `README.md`** |

Also update **`README.md`** whenever contributor-facing facts change (see above). **README and `.mdc` should move together** for the same facts.

**Are we doing it in practice?** Only if every change follows the table. When you notice drift (e.g. backend `.mdc` still describing dropped tables), **fix the `.mdc` in the same fix** as the code correction.

**Drizzle workflow (`backend/`):**

- **Source of truth:** `src/database/schemas/` (TypeScript). Do **not** add or edit `.sql` files under `drizzle/` by hand, and do **not** manually edit `drizzle/meta/` (snapshots, `_journal.json`) — **Drizzle Kit** owns that state when you run **`npm run db:generate`**.
- **`npm run db:generate`** — diffs schema → writes the next migration SQL + updates `meta/`. Use whenever the schema changes.
- **`npm run db:migrate`** — applies pending migrations to the database (reads migrations + `__drizzle_migrations` on the server). It does **not** generate SQL; generation is **`db:generate`** only.
- **One-off / emergency SQL** (e.g. fix prod data, exploratory column drop): use a **temporary** script or Neon SQL editor, run it, then **delete** the temp file — do **not** commit ad-hoc SQL into `drizzle/` unless it came from **`db:generate`**.

**Docs (cross-cutting):** New modules or cross-cutting patterns deserve a short **why** (intent, tradeoff), not a restatement of the code. API **request/response** shapes stay documented—OpenAPI / DTOs are part of that contract.

**Collaboration:** **Share your plan first** (goal, files you will touch, tradeoffs) and **get explicit agreement before writing substantial code**, unless the user has already approved the approach or the task is trivial (typo, one-liner). The intent is to **code together** with the user steering—not to sprint ahead solo.
